BkNt8Jj90T4.title: Agatha All Along... but it reminds me of Tim Burton (cover ft. Brian Hull)
BkNt8Jj90T4.description:
Spoilers for WandaVision Season 1! Agatha All Along is clearly the bop of the century so you know we had to do it.
Listen to more mind-blowing covers from Brian Hull: https://www.youtube.com/user/hullbkh
Listen to this amazing orchestral cover by L'Orchestra Cinématique without the vocals: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fGS7TYmIZOQ
And loads more incredible covers from L'Orchestra Cinématique: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCLuEtEE-MF7EYtGcN0Z6mDg

"Agatha All Along" is from WandaVision and written by Kristen Anderson-Lopez and Robert Lopez
Orchestral cover by L'Orchestra Cinématique
Señor Scratchy played and sung by Brian Hull
Vocals mixed and edited by Alex Green
Sparky played by Remus

84_YEaWXI94.title: I'm worried about YouTube and my channel. (COPPA)
84_YEaWXI94.description:
Please. Write a simple, polite, thoughtful comment to the FTC sharing your thoughts on how this isn't the right decision:
Sign the Official Petition: http://chng.it/kLnwsSJzFv
Leave a COMMENT for the FTC: https://www.regulations.gov/document?D=FTC-2019-0054-0001
Suggested Talking Points for Viewers: https://bit.ly/2Wptf1U
Suggested Talking Points for Creators: https://bit.ly/31SwLmI
See comments written by others: https://bit.ly/31ZefJi
Brian Hull's Video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v7pn0gBTO9g
COPPA: everything you need to know: https://youtu.be/1b9HGNHm-aQ
Why COPPA is so scary for creators: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0veLrwd9CK4
MatPat's video on COPPA: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pd604xskDmU

example of what you can write:
Dear FTC members, 
I am a (content creator/viewer/parent). I would urge you to rethink the current rules and how vague they are. Just because a percentage of the children watching a genre are children doesn't mean you have an obligation to remove all forms of personalization. Watching this content, I would prefer targeted ads that show my actual interests rather than random car or horror film ads. Leave the parenting to parents who make the decision to give their child access to YouTube. If this decision goes through, family-friendly content on YouTube will suffer and families will suffer for it. Content creators do their best to create great content and threatening legal action against individuals over the opinion of "child appealing" is excessive.  Please don't ruin one of the most important websites on the internet to me.
